Prompt-injection hardening — Odysseus
--------------------------------------
The brain's prompt-safety design is modeled on Odysseus, a self-hosted AI
workspace by PewDiePie, licensed under the MIT License.

    Source:  https://github.com/pewdiepie-archdaemon/odysseus
    License: MIT

The following components adapt patterns from Odysseus (read from source, not
copied verbatim; re-implemented for this codebase):

  - api/security/untrusted.py
        The untrusted-context wrapper (UNTRUSTED_CONTEXT_POLICY preamble,
        do-not-follow header, user-role data-block message shape, and
        delimiter neutralization) adapts Odysseus's src/prompt_security.py and
        its rule that injecting untrusted content into the system role is a
        security bug.

  - api/tools/__init__.py  (is_blocked_tool + the dispatch gate)
        The fail-closed dangerous-tool gate — non-string name -> blocked,
        mcp__* admin-only, default-deny for shell/file/email/settings families
        — adapts Odysseus's src/tool_security.py:is_public_blocked_tool and its
        "if I can't evaluate it, deny" principle.

  - THREAT_MODEL.md
        Adopts the practice of shipping a one-page brain-facing threat model
        with an explicit Known Gaps section, after Odysseus's THREAT_MODEL.md.

